Use ASP.NET Core's **`WebApplicationFactory<T>`** — it hosts your app in-memory and gives you an `HttpClient` that talks to it without opening a real port.

```csharp
// MyMcpTests.cs
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing;
using System.Net.Http.Json;
using Xunit;

public class McpIntegrationTests
    : IClassFixture<WebApplicationFactory<Program>>
{
    private readonly HttpClient _client;

    public McpIntegrationTests(WebApplicationFactory<Program> factory)
    {
        _client = factory.CreateClient();
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task Initialize_ReturnsCapabilities()
    {
        var request = new
        {
            jsonrpc = "2.0",
            id = 1,
            method = "initialize",
            @params = new
            {
                protocolVersion = "2025-03-26",
                clientInfo = new { name = "test", version = "1.0" },
                capabilities = new { }
            }
        };

        var response = await _client.PostAsJsonAsync("/mcp", request);

        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        var body = await response.Content.ReadFromJsonAsync<JsonElement>();
        Assert.Equal("2025-03-26",
            body.GetProperty("result")
                .GetProperty("protocolVersion")
                .GetString());
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task ToolsCall_ExecutesTool()
    {
        // initialize first, then call a tool
        // ... (initialize as above) ...

        var callRequest = new
        {
            jsonrpc = "2.0",
            id = 2,
            method = "tools/call",
            @params = new
            {
                name = "my-tool",
                arguments = new { input = "hello" }
            }
        };

        var response = await _client.PostAsJsonAsync("/mcp", callRequest);
        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- **No real port** — `WebApplicationFactory` creates an in-process `TestServer`; the `HttpClient` routes requests directly to it.
- **Full pipeline** — middleware, DI, routing, serialization all run exactly as in production.
- **Override services** — use `factory.WithWebHostBuilder(b => b.ConfigureServices(...))` to swap in test doubles (e.g., mock databases).
- **SSE support** — for Streamable HTTP (`text/event-stream`), read the response stream incrementally with `HttpCompletionOption.ResponseHeadersRead`.
- **Endpoint path** — adjust `"/mcp"` to match your actual MCP endpoint route.

Add the `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing` NuGet package to your test project and ensure your server project exposes a `Program` class (top-level statements do this automatically in .NET 6+).
